content.description: Starting to the the right side of the vulcan roof (horizontal roof right of the main cave overhang) it goes up and out left in the roof for 10 feet or so through cool pockets then up onto the technical face above using the 'vulcan hold'

Fun, short, overhanging climb that leaves you with a slight pump.  The crux is trying to figure out how to clip the 4th bolt (it isn't very intuitive, and you don't need to use the small sloper/crimp).
content.location: This is the climb across from Bolt Ladder.  It is the overhanging face just left of the arete.

content.description: Fun route and an easy warm-up for the area.  Climbs the Unknown 5.11c just right of the dihedral route at the far right edge of the cave up to the no-hands rest ledge, then traverses left to the anchors of the dihedral route.  Crux seemed to be between the 2nd and 3rd bolts where it is a bit thinner.  Fun easy, but still kind of techy route.
content.protection: 4 or 5 bolts to the chain anchors atop the dihedral route.
content.location: At the right edge of the cave is an obvious dihedral with a crack, this is the dihedral route, this is the first bolted route to the right of the dihedral route and ends at the anchors to that route.

content.description:
This is first bolted line right of the cave. The route heads straight up on side pulls and crimps before gaining a no hands rest ledge. A few moves puts you into a right trending corner for three bolts and finishes on a thin face (crux).

Stopping at the ledge there is a set of chains to the left that makes for a nice warm up. 5.10 range.
content.location: First bolted line right of the cave.

content.description: Not really sure of the rating on this one.  It felt kind of difficult.  Maybe 5.10c-5.11a??  Who knows?  The crux is from the 3rd bolt all the way to the end.  The moves are thin and tricky.
content.protection: 5 or 6 bolts to some chains with fixed QDs.
content.location: Just right of Doggie Doo.  Unless this is Doggie doo, but it didn't seem that hard.

content.description:
Aid or jump to the big jug on the right side of horizontal roof (which ends the V9 boulder problem start).  Traverse up and left through two bolts.  Climb straight up past three more bolts. Continue up to 'Coast to Coast' and finish on 'Crimp Fest'.

This route is mostly big moves on pretty good holds with a devious start along the lip (bolts 2-3).  I'm guessing the grade is height dependent and a few moves are easier for taller folks.
content.protection: 9ish (usually fixed) draws with chain anchors( usually fixed biners)
content.location: Start on the huge jug near the lip on the right side of the prominent horizontal roof of china cave.  As you walk towards the Oboe boulder from the entrance, you'll see the obvious chalked jug rail on the roof about 10 ft before reaching the boulder.

content.description:
Tricky and beta intensive, Trench Warfare follows a horizontal, left-trending crack using good but difficult to use holds and lots of kneebars.  Although this route follows a crack, there are no jams so you don't need to tape up.

Start by climbing up the white mound at the base of the cave.  An extended V8 boulder problem with a few drilled pockets brings you to better holds and your first kneebar rest.  Keep following the crack, and using kneebars until you are below the final bulge.  Big pulls and awkwardly facing holds get you into a steep corner and to the chains.
content.protection: Bolts and two bolt anchor.  Two kneepads.
content.location: Look for the obvious white mound at the back of the cave with a black, left-trending crack above it.

content.description:
Contrived?  Yes.

Make take the claim as the silliest route at China Cave.  Climb Coast To Coast To Coast To Oboe.  Kneebars, etc.
content.location: Oboe start, coast to coast forwards, coast to coast backwards to where coast and oboe diverge, finish on Oboe.

content.description: The first .14B in America. Do the V9 boulder problem into Tweak, but finish directly up the headwall into another V9.
Super Tweak to easier Crimpfest finish
content.location: Starts on v-9 at back of the cave finishes on crimp fest

content.description: Climb Coast to Coast into the short dihedral above the second major crack system/kneebar.  Clip the draw before the second kneebar on coast and make way to the dihedral/roof.
content.protection: 10ish draws and chain anchors (most likely with biners)
content.location: Boulder start for Oboe.

content.description:
Start on the big juggy rail at the end of the Super Tweak boulder problem.  Traverse left four bolts before heading up and left following a dihedral of sorts.  Finish on Crimpfest.

Brilliant route with excellent movement.
Starts on the jug to the left of trench warfare climbs out drilled pockets and finish’s on Coast to Coast anchors.
content.location:
Start on jug left of trench warfare finish on coast to coast

anchors.

content.description:
"Allow me to demonstrate the skill of Shaolin / The special technique of shadowboxing"

Shadowboxin' is a mixed route in the cave. Climb the first four bolts of Blank Out/Moratorium and then break left in the obvious roof crack. A little dusty  and a little spicy up top. Trad limestone in the cave...what do you expect?

There was once a few bolts here but the line was never finished and the bolts were pulled. Apparently it was poorly manufactured and then got chopped from what I've heard.
content.protection: 4 bolts, hand sized pieces. Nuts for the top (if my fixed nut isn’t their anymore) Bring a 5 or a big bro equivalent.
content.location: Start on first 4 bolts of Moratorium/Blank Out, then break left into the roof crack, pull the roof, finish on spicy vert.

content.description: Shares the same start as Oboe up to the crack. From the crack follow the first set of pre hung draws to the right. Using small crimps and a mono you'll pull yourself onto the head wall for a techy finish to the anchors.
content.location: The route is in between Oboe and Cunning Runt. You start the route by standing on the large boulder and using the drilled pockets to get on the roof.

content.description: Sustained no specific crux
content.location: Start on Praise the lowered finish on the minnow

content.description:
Great line on the "slabby" part of the China Wall! Actually, this line is pretty much vertical with sections of gently overhanging stone, so don't expect a slab climb!  This route doesn't have many sharp holds - they are pretty kind on the skin.  The climbing involves difficult face maneuvers with reachy moves, lots of sidepulls, and tricky feet.Praise the Lowered is well protected but not overly so - you will be pulling some cruxes above bolts - the way God intended them to be done!

This is about the 3rd line right of "Gang of Four" on the vertical wall.  It follows a very obvious black streak up the wall.

One of the cave-dwelling locals over on the steep stuff once told me that this line was well known as the best "slab" route to do at the China Wall.  I had to agree. Get on it!

Climb the crack to the Vulcan roof ( large pocketed steep roof above the Oboe boulder).  Traverse to the Oboe kneebar (first large crack system).  Finish on the oboe.

Crux comes midway through the Vulcan roof.  Fight the pump to the end.  Super fun movement!
content.protection: Lots of bolts, need one draw for the first bolt, the rest are fixed.

content.description:
Super juggy route with a hard move near the top.  This route is easy 12, and is the standard warm up route at this crag.Really fun and totally worthwhile, either as a warmup or as an objective all of it's own.

Pretty obvious jug haul on the far right side of the cave.
Do Blank Out but continue straight up the headwall (left most line of bolts).  A reachy move leaving Coast to Coast may present problems depending on your height.
content.location: Follows the left-most line of fixed draws at China Cave.

content.description: Climbs coast to coast and finish’s on bulletproof Monk. Crux is a big throw off decent holds to a jug. 12d/13a?
content.location: Starts on oboe, climbs about half of coast to coast and then go’s up the next draws to the left of crimpfest.

content.description: Stewart Green calls this a "Technical Masterpiece" in the Climbing Utah book.  Delicate face climbing up perfect limestone for 90 feet. 10 Bolts to 2 bolt anchor. a 60m rope is needed to lower off.
content.location: Right of the Cave 20-30 feet.  I think it's the first route right of the Dihedral Route.

content.description: Climb vulcan roof to secret sharer
content.location: natural line out vulcan roof

climbs.name: Gang of Four
climbs.fa: Kelly Oldroyd, Boone Speed, Bill Boyle, Ralph Mitchell

content.description:
The easiest route on the China Wall Cave.  This route is kind of interesting and worth doing if you are there.  The bolts are a bit spaced out.

Go to the far right side of the cave and climb up and then traverse left.The route is not steep at all but it does trend up along the contour of the cave, so your feet are perched just above open air - kind of nice position.

Now go do something hard!

Start Coast-to-coast and take the second to last exit (between moratorium and sportfest).  Longest finish in the cave?

Hard moves off coast lead to technical runout terrain above.
content.location: Start off the boulder (Oboe/coast-to-coast start).

content.description: Interesting crack and lay-back climbing leads to technical crux to a series of finishing jugs.
content.location: This route is in the middle of the wall and begins directly to the right of "Praise the Lowered" and begins up the obvious crack.

content.description: Climb The Big Brawl straight up into the Monkfest finish. The cleanest variation of the line.
If you've never done a chimney climb before and you're sick of screaming as you hang from dime edges... take a break and abuse your whole body on this fun chimney.
content.protection: Gear up to 3 inches.  Plenty of cracks on the side walls, so throw in as much as you want.
content.location: Obvious chimney on the far right.

content.description:
This crack is located between Gang of Four.and another unknown route just left of Minnow Maker.

Size ranges from thin fingers to wide hands, and involves a good amount of stemming. Just before the obvious crux there are some nice pockets on the left face to make your placement. I ran the crux out (not recommended) but there is a bomber spot for a red c4.
content.protection:
Standard small to midsize rack, and a couple small nuts.

There are sling anchors at the top, although you can make a small traverse to the anchors of the unknown route to the right.
content.location: Far right side of the cave. You can't miss this crack. It goes right up next to the "Vulcan Roof".

content.description:
Climb coast to coast until heading straight up at the first kneebar/crack system past Oboe.  The crux is an awesome 4-5 move boulder problem off of Coast to Coast. Afterwards, continue straight up on relatively easy climbing.

The guide book rates it at 13b, while people rate it anywhere from 12d-13b if you care.  Height dependent?
content.protection: 10ish fixed draws and chain anchors (with biners)
content.location: Oboe boulder start

content.description:
Start at the base of Oboe (obvious 5.12 on the far right side of the cave) and traverse all the way across the cave to the left.Super juggy - how can it be so hard?  Well, it is steep, and the jugs are slippery, and some of the movement between them is downright weird.

If you are up to do a traverse, this is really cool.  Of course, it is imperative that you make sure that Yuji or Francois or somebody isn't going up Super Tweak or one of the other caver routes, or they will be irritated that you are hogging the whole crag.
content.protection: 10 bolts? This is approximate - bring a few extra.

content.description: Climb through the vulcan roof and finish on crimpfest.  Fun link up!
content.location: Start on vulcan roof.

content.description: Extends 4 bolts + anchors at the finish off of bolt ladder. feels just like the climbing on bolt ladder just longer and some bigger moves.
content.protection: just quickdraws and a belayer will do. probably a rope as well. (use your own discretion)
content.location: rightmost route on china wall before the chimney

content.description: Hardest move is to the jug at the anchors
Start on the Tweak jug and go straight up and right to the Oboe anchors. Watch your tendons as it can involve lunging into a mono before going right.
Climb coast to coast and then straight up the last bolted line (Moratorium).  After coast, the route is mostly great feeling two finger pockets. Fun route.
content.protection: 14ish fixed draws and chain anchors with biners.
content.location: Boulder start.  Climb Coast to Coast to the last draw before the anchors and head straight up through two more draws

content.description: A well designed route involving fun gymnastic moves on big holds.  Finishes on Coast to Coast anchors.
content.protection: Fixed Petzl draws. Stick-clip or rodeo for the first clip encouraged.
content.location: Most left fixed line of draws.

content.description: Crux is at 7th bolt
content.location: Same start as Slugfest finish on Sport finish.  It was one of the original routes

content.description: Easier terrain through the first three bolts leads to a huge jug.  From the jug to the first 'ledge' it's on.  Fun tension moves lead to a cruxy sequence of crimps and welcome jugs in a spacey feeling section near the ledge.  Rest on the ledge for a big move near the top.
content.location: To the left of bolt ladder and right of first blood (obvious crack) on the china 'slab'.

content.description:
Start on the Vulcan crawl (horizontal pocketed roof to the left of the crack, climb the crack to the roof).  Climb the Vulcan roof into the Oboe knee bar (first crack system).  Continue to the finish of Coast to Coast.

The crux comes midway through the roof (after Vulcan Crawl veers out to the face).  The sequence through the roof is excellent.  Fight the pump to a plethora of different finishes.
content.protection: Lots of bolts.  One draw for the first bolt, the rest are fixed.

content.description: Start on the ticked large incut jug for your left hand and the 2-3 finger pocket for your right hand.  You may need some blocks to reach the starting holds.  Make a huge throw for a pocket and climb straight up and finish on Oboe.
content.protection: Lots of bolts.  The oboe finish is typically fixed.  The bottom three bolts of bassoon may not be.
content.location: The starting holds are located on the roof below the oboe start in between the tweak jug and the oboe starting boulder.
